408:/*
409:    The third critical signal for DRAM access is the MUX signal which switches the address lines on the DRAM
410:    from the ROW to the COLUMN address.  This much be done after the RAS signal has gone to 0, and before the 
411:    CAS signal goes to 0.  There is RAS holdtime requirement of 10ns, and CAS setup requirement if 10ns, and a 
412:    MUX propegation delay of at least 7ns.
413:
414:    The solution is the change the MUX signal based on the DRAM_ACCESS_RAS signal.  As soon as the RAS signal goes low, 
415:    the MUX signal will start to change.  The MUX change will be 7.5ns behind the RAS signal, and the MUX itself
416:    will take another 7ns to change outputs.  This will give the needed RAS hold time.
417:
418:    MUX = 0 for ROW address, 1 for COL address.  Reset puts it at 0. 
419:*/
